04635nam a22006855i 9780271090993DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710909937 a10.1515/97802710909932doi  a(DE-B1597)586171  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBR307b.B82 2014eb 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a274/.062231 aBuck, Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Roman Monster :bAn Icon of the Papal Antichrist In Reformation Polemics /cLawrence Buck. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly Modern Studies ;v1300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: The Roman Monster: Historical Context -- tChapter 1: The Roman Monster of 1496 -- tChapter 2: The Roman Monster in the Kingdom of Bohemia 1498-1523 -- tChapter 3: The Papal Antichrist -- tChapter 4: Philip Melanchthon's The Pope-Ass Explained (1523) -- tChapter 5: The Diffusion of the Roman Monster within the Discourse of the Reformation -- tConclusion The Pope-Ass as a Trope of Antipapalism in Reformation Politics -- tAppendix: The Pope-Ass Explained (1523) by Philip Melanchthon -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn December 1495 the Tiber River flooded the city of Rome causing extensive drowning and destruction. When the water finally receded, a rumor began to circulate that a grotesque monstrosity had been discovered in the muddy detritus-the Roman monster. The creature itself is inherently fascinating, consisting of an eclectic combination of human and animal body parts. The symbolism of these elements, the interpretations that religious controversialists read into them, and the history of the image itself, help to document antipapal polemics from fifteenth-century Rome to the Elizabethan religious settlement.This study examines the iconography of the image of the Roman monster and offers ideological reasons for associating the image with the pre-Reformation Waldensians and Bohemian Brethren. It accounts for the reproduction and survival of the monster&apos;s image in fifteenth-century Bohemia and provides historical background on the topos of the papal Antichrist, a concept that Philip Melanchthon associated with the monster. It contextualizes Melanchthon's tract, "The Pope-Ass Explained," within the first five years of the Lutheran movement, and it documents the popularity of the Roman monster within the polemical and apocalyptic writings of the Reformation.This is a careful examination and interpretation of all relevant primary documents and secondary historical literature in telling the story of the origins and impact of the most famous monstrous portent of the Reformation era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnti-CatholicismxHistory. 0aMonstersxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory. 0aPapacyxHistory. 0aReformation. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074525240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271090993zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271090993423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271090993.jpg  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK